frameDefinitions: A Protagonist is in the dynamic, maintained state of being alive or has exited this state.
An Entity is declared to exist, generally irrespective of its position or even the possibility of its position being specified.
A Protagonist is awake at some Time and Place.
The frame concerns the vehicles that human beings use for the purpose of transportation.
An Entity is evaluated for whether or not it belongs to a particular Reference_category in a context where its category membership is doubtful.
frameExamples: Finally, Poland ceased to <t>exist</t> as a state for hundreds of years.
I drove a <t>limo</t> to the school dance.

It can be hard to get your money back after discovering you've bought a <t>bogus</t>
autograph for hundreds or thousands of dollars!
listRoleDefinitions: <fen>Protagonist</fen> identifies the being or entity that is  dead or alive.
This role identifies the <fen>Figure</fen> or form being described by the target.
The time in which the <fen>Protagonist</fen> is dead or alive.
Some entity, abstract or concrete, which is stated to exist.
A time at which the entity is in existence.
The entity that is not sleeping.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Protagonist</fen> is awake.
Vehicle is the transportation device that the human beings use to travel.This role is incorporated into each LU in this frame.
The <fen>Entity</fen> that is being evaluated in terms of whether it is an instance of the <fen>Reference_category</fen>.
The type relative to which the <fen>Entity</fen> is evaluated.
listRoleExamples: <fex>She</fex> was awake through the whole football game.
<fex>The bomb found at the US Embassy in Berlin</fex> was fake.
